        routeDescription: "The route follows the A55 towards Martigues/Fos, along the Côte Bleue and the Étang de Berre.",
        introduction: "Martigues, nicknamed the Provençal Venice for its picturesque canals lined with colourful houses, is a destination unknown to most international tourists but beloved by Marseillais and Provençaux. The Île quarter, the town's historic heart, offers a unique spectacle with its pastel façades reflected in the calm waters of the Saint-Sébastien canal — the 'Miroir aux Oiseaux' (Bird Mirror) is one of Provence's most photographed and most painted sites, immortalised by Félix Ziem and other Impressionist painters. Martigues is also an authentic Mediterranean fishing port, the most important in the Bouches-du-Rhône after Marseille, famous for its poutargue (bottarga), those dried and pressed mullet roe pouches that constitute a delicacy highly prized by gastronomes. The town is bordered by the Étang de Berre on one side and the Mediterranean on the other, with the wild beaches of the Côte Bleue (Carro, La Couronne) just a few kilometres away. Every summer, free sardinades on the port attract thousands of diners to enjoy wood-fire grilled sardines. A taxi is the most comfortable way to reach Martigues from Marseille, as public transport is limited outside peak hours.",
