        introduction: "Pertuis, a charming town of 20,000 inhabitants nestled at the foot of the Luberon's southern slopes, is the southern gateway to this massif classified as a Regional Natural Park. A former stronghold of the Counts of Forcalquier, the town retains an attractive medieval centre with 14th-century towers, the Saint-Nicolas church with its Renaissance facade and the keep of the former castle overlooking the old town. Pertuis is also the ideal starting point for exploring the perched villages of the southern Luberon: Lourmarin (6 km), Cadenet, Cucuron, Ansouis and Vaugines, all immortalised in cinema and Provencal literature. The town hosts a lively Provencal market on Friday mornings that rivals those of its more famous neighbours. From Marseille, a taxi via the A51 is the fastest and most comfortable way to reach this Luberon gateway, avoiding the constraints of Pertuis's outlying station and bus connections. Families renting a cottage in the Luberon particularly appreciate the door-to-door transfer with luggage from Marseille airport or station.",
