      en: {
        metaTitle: "Taxi Marseille → Lourmarin | 68 km, from €90 | TaxiNeo",
        metaDescription: "Direct route via A51 then D973, 55 min. Château Renaissance, Albert Camus, Luberon sud and Village perché en route. Stops for sightseeing possible en route.",
        heroTitle: "Taxi Marseille → Lourmarin",
        heroSubtitle: "Your Marseille → Lourmarin transfer at a fixed price of €90 — €115. Route via A51 and D973. Online booking.",
        description: "The Marseille — Lourmarin route connects the Phocaean city to the Luberon's most famous village, listed among France's Most Beautiful Villages. 68 km via the A51 then southern Luberon roads.",
        routeDescription: "The route follows the A51 to Pertuis, then the D973 through vineyards and cherry orchards of the southern Luberon to Lourmarin.",
        introduction: "Lourmarin, listed among France's Most Beautiful Villages (Plus Beaux Villages de France), is the jewel of the Luberon's southern slopes and one of Provence's most celebrated villages. Its chateau, the first Renaissance castle built in Provence, overlooks lanes of plane trees and mossy fountains that give this village of 1,100 inhabitants its incomparable charm. Albert Camus, Nobel Prize for Literature, bought a house here in 1958 and rests in the communal cemetery — his simply adorned grave is a literary pilgrimage site. Lourmarin enchants with its artistic yet village atmosphere: art galleries, ceramics workshops, bookshops and gourmet restaurants line the shaded squares where you sip coffee watching children play by the fountain. On Friday mornings, the Provencal market fills the centre in an explosion of colours and scents. The village is the ideal starting point for exploring the southern Luberon (Cucuron, Ansouis, Vaugines) and crossing the Lourmarin combe to the perched villages of the northern Luberon (Bonnieux, Lacoste, Menerbes). From Marseille, a taxi is the most suitable transfer, especially for families heading to a holiday rental in the Luberon.",
        itineraire: "Departing from Marseille, your driver takes the A51 (Val de Durance motorway) northward, bypassing Aix-en-Provence to the east. After the Pertuis exit, the D973 crosses the AOC Luberon vineyards and cherry orchards that make the southern Luberon famous. The landscapes become increasingly bucolic: scrubland hills, dry stone walls, lavender fields (in season) and centuries-old olive groves. The approach to Lourmarin follows a plane-tree-lined road offering a first view of the Renaissance chateau and the Romanesque bell tower of Saint-Andre church. The village is compact and largely pedestrianised. Your driver can drop you at the main car park (2 minutes' walk from the centre), in front of the chateau or directly at your accommodation if vehicle-accessible. The journey takes about 55 minutes, potentially reaching 1h20 during rush hours around Aix-en-Provence. Tolls on the A51 total approximately 5 euros.",
        conseils: "Lourmarin market is held on Friday mornings around the fountain square and adjacent lanes — it is one of the Luberon's finest, with local producers (goat's cheese, honey, olive oil, fruits). The Chateau de Lourmarin (Provence's first Renaissance castle) is open year-round: do not miss the belfry and furnished salons. Albert Camus's grave in the communal cemetery is discreet but moving — the cemetery is at the top of the village with Luberon views. For lunch, La Recreation and Le Moulin de Lourmarin are the standout addresses. The Lourmarin combe (D943) crosses the massif to Bonnieux in 15 minutes — spectacular cedar forest scenery. In summer, parking fills up by 10am: by taxi, you avoid this problem. To explore the Luberon from Lourmarin, the hourly hire formula is perfect: Cucuron (7 km), Ansouis (9 km), Bonnieux (12 km via the combe). In the evenings, free concerts on the village square in summer create a magical atmosphere.",
        comparaisonTransport: "There is no railway station or direct bus to Lourmarin. The nearest public transport is the TER to Pertuis (1h10, 12 euros) then 6 km with no regular transport to Lourmarin. By car, expect 10 euros in fuel and 5 euros in tolls, totalling 15 euros excluding parking (difficult in summer). The TaxiNeo taxi at 90 to 115 euros is the only door-to-door solution from Marseille. For 3-4 passengers (23 to 38 euros per person), it is essential for families with luggage arriving by plane or train in Marseille and heading to a Luberon rental.",
        faq: [
          { question: "Can I visit Lourmarin chateau?", answer: "Yes, the chateau is open year-round (10am-5:30pm in winter, 10am-6:30pm in summer). Admission: 7 euros for adults. It is Provence's first Renaissance castle, with magnificent furnished rooms and views over the village." },
          { question: "Where is Albert Camus's grave?", answer: "Albert Camus's grave is in Lourmarin's communal cemetery, at the top of the village. A simple grave, adorned with flowers by visitors from around the world. The cemetery is open daily." },
          { question: "Can we continue to Bonnieux or Gordes from Lourmarin?", answer: "Yes, Bonnieux is 12 km via the Lourmarin combe (15 min), Gordes 30 km (30 min). Your driver can take you there. Supplement of 15 to 35 euros depending on the destination." },
          { question: "Is there public transport to Lourmarin?", answer: "No, Lourmarin has no regular public transport service. The nearest station is Pertuis (6 km). A taxi is the only door-to-door option." },
          { question: "Can the taxi pick me up from Marseille Provence Airport to Lourmarin?", answer: "Yes, Marignane airport is 72 km from Lourmarin (55 min via A7 then A51). The driver meets you in arrivals with a name board." }
        ],
      },
