        introduction: "Fréjus, founded by Julius Caesar in 49 BC under the name Forum Julii, is one of the oldest Roman cities in Gaul. Its exceptional ancient heritage includes a Roman amphitheatre (one of France's oldest, seating 10,000 spectators), an aqueduct with surviving imposing arches, remains of the ancient port (the second Roman military port after Ostia) and a Roman theatre. The Fréjus episcopal group (cathedral, baptistery, cloister), dating from the 5th to 13th centuries, is one of France's best-preserved early Christian ensembles. Fréjus is also the gateway to the Estérel massif, a geological wonder of red porphyry rocks plunging into the turquoise Mediterranean. The fine sand beaches of Fréjus-Plage and Saint-Aygulf, the Estérel calanques (Petit Caneiret cove, Maubois inlet) and the Base Nature François Léotard (135 hectares of preserved coastal nature) offer an exceptional seaside setting. Saint-Raphaël, Fréjus's twin city, complements the offer with its marina, Belle Époque villas and underwater archaeological museum. The city hosts an annual comic book festival and the Nuits Auréliennes (performances in the amphitheatre).",
